value.value: Human WNT7A wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 3p25 and is approximately 14 kb in length. This allele, which encodes protein wnt-7a, is involved in embryonic cell fate determination.
A meningioma that is transmitted from the parents to an offspring.

Human LHX1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 17q12 and is approximately 6 kb in length. This allele, which encodes LIM/homeobox 1 protein Lhx1, may play a role in the regulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II and the development of lymphoid and neural cells.

Human LHX2 wild-type allele is located within 9q33-34.1 and is approximately 22 kb in length. This allele, which encodes the LIM/homeobox protein Lhx2, may play a role in both the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II and the development of lymphoid and neural cells.

Human MSX1 wild-type allele is located within 4p16.3-16.1 and is approximately 4 kb in length. This allele, which encodes homeobox protein MSX-1, is involved in both the repression of transcription by RNA polymerase II and the development of teeth and limbs.

Human NKX2-8 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 14q13.3 and is approximately 3 kb in length. This allele, which encodes homeobox protein Nkx-2.8, is involved in the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II in several developmental processes.
An artery arising from the subscapular artery that supplies the muscles in the upper back.

Human NKX3-1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 8p21 and is approximately 4 kb in length. This allele, which encodes homeobox protein Nkx-3.1, plays a role in the suppression of transcription by RNA polymerase II, the proliferation of glandular epithelium and the development of ducts in the prostate.
A meningioma that affects the lateral ventricle of the brain.
A short arterial segment arising from the first segment of the subclavian artery that branches to form the inferior and superior thyroid arteries.

An artery that is the first branch of the external carotid artery that supplies the upper thyroid gland and its muscles and branches to form the crico-thyroid, hyoid, sterno-mastoid and superior laryngeal arteries.
One of the three branches of the thyroid axis that supplies the thyroid gland and branches to form the ascending cervical, esophageal, inferior laryngeal, muscular and tracheal arteries.

An artery that can arise from the innominate (brachiocephalic) artery, aortic arch, internal mammary artery, right common carotid artery, or the subclavian artery to supply the lower portion of the thyroid gland.

Human JUN wild-type allele is located within 1p32-p31 and is approximately 4 kb in length. This allele, which encodes transcription factor AP-1 protein, is involved in the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II.
An artery arising from the superficial temporal artery that supplies the masseter muscle and corresponding skin as well as the parotid duct and parotid gland.

Human JUNB wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19p13.2 and is approximately 2 kb in length. This allele, which encodes transcription factor jun-B protein, plays a role in the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II.
A vein that drains the auricle and acoustic meatus of the external ear.

Human JUND wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19p13.2 and is approximately 2 kb in length. This allele, which encodes transcription factor jun-D protein, plays a role in the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II.
A blood vessel which returns blood to the heart from the posterior walls of the thorax and abdomen.
An ectopic meningioma that arises from the parapharyngeal space.

Human AFF3 wild-type allele is located within 2q11.2-q12 and is approximately 595 kb in length. This allele, which encodes AF4/FRM2 family member 3 protein, may play roles in both the activation of RNA polymerase II-directed transcription and the development of lymphoid tissues. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia is associated with rearrangement and fusion of this gene to the MLL gene.
The veins that drain the bronchi then form two branches where the right side drains into the right azygos vein and the left side drains into the left superior intercostal or left upper azygos vein.
A superficial vein that is located on the cerebellum and that drains the cerebellum.

Human LMO2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11p13 and is approximately 34 kb in length. This allele, which encodes rhombotin-2 protein, is involved in red blood cell development through the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II.

Human MAF wild-type allele is located within 16q22-q23 and is approximately 6 kb in length. This allele, which encodes transcription factor MAF protein, is involved in the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II.

Human MAFG wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 17q25.3 and is approximately 9 kb in length. This allele, which encodes transcription factor MafG protein, plays a role in the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II.

Human MAX wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 14q23 and is approximately 93 kb in length. This allele, which encodes protein max, plays a role in both the modulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II and chromatin remodeling.
Any of the external or internal veins that drain the cerebral hemispheres.

One of the three parts of the spinalis muscle, which takes its origin from the spinous processes of the upper thoracic vertebrae, and which inserts into the spinous processes of the eleventh and twelfth thoracic and first and second lumbar vertebrae; it functions to support and extend the vertebral column.
A group of muscles causing movement of the leg towards the midline of the body.
Meningiomas that affects both optic nerves.
A vein that drains blood from a specific area of the skin.
A group of muscles including the biceps femoris, semimembranosus and semitendinosus that extend down the back of the thigh.
Any vein containing deoxygenated blood that is located in a finger or toe.

A skeletal muscle belonging to the infrahyoid muscle group, located in the anterior part of the neck, with its origin on the sternum and its insertion on the hyoid bone; it functions to depress the hyoid bone and larynx during swallowing and speaking.
Either of two veins including the inferior and superior epigastric veins.
The veins that drain blood from the ileum into the superior mesenteric vein.
A blood vessel running parallel to the ileocolic artery that drains blood from the terminal ileum and ascending colon into the superior mesenteric vein.
A blood vessel running parallel to the iliolumbar artery connected to the deep circumflex iliac and lumbar veins that drains into the internal iliac vein.
The blood vessels that drain blood from the inferior eyelid into the angular vein.
A meningioma that is associated with deletion of chromosome 22.  This abnormality is the most consistent cytogenetic finding that is detected in meningiomas.

The veins arising in the right and left testicles that join to form the spermatic plexus then diverge with the left segment draining into the left renal vein and the right into the inferior vena cava.
The veins that drain blood from the masseter muscle into the pterygoid venous plexus.
An artery arising from the maxillary artery that supplies the deep surface of the masseter muscle.
A particular category of events regarded as having particular characteristics, qualities, and/or defined similarities.

An issue with quality, authenticity, performance, or/and safety of medication or medical device. The concept encompasses any problems that may occur during manufacturing, shipping, storage, or use of the medical product including but not limited to such concerns as suspect counterfeit product, product contamination, super potent or subpotent medication, defective item or its component, poor packaging or product confusion, questionable stability, device failure or malfunction, and labeling concerns.
One of two veins (inferior or superior) that returns deoxygenated blood from the intestines.
